<HEADLINE>
<P>
TENNIS ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
WHEATON, GARRISON WIN SINGLES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PERTH, Australia 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
David Wheaton defeated Petr Korda 6-4, 6-2 and Zina Garrison beat Regina 
Rajchrtova 6-4, 6-4 today as the United States advanced the semifinals of the 
Hopman Cup team tennis tournament with a 2-1 victory over Czechoslovakia. 
</P>
<P>
Korda and Rajchrtova recovered to beat the American pair 8-1 in a mixed doubles 
match that was reduced to one professional set after the top-seeded United 
States clinched the match with a 2-0 lead. 
</P>
<P>
"I think it was tough for both Zina and me, because we hadn't played for a 
while," Wheaton said. "I certainly felt a little out of it." 
</P>
<P>
Garrison was returning to tennis after a monthlong vacation. "I'm only just 
getting back into the flow of tennis after not playing since the Virginia Slims 
championship a month ago," she said. 
</P>
<P>
The United States will face the Swiss team of Jakob Hlasek and Manuela 
Maleeva-Fragniere in the semifinals on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
Akiko Kijimuta of Japan beat comeback-minded Pam Shriver 6-4, 6-2 today in the 
first round of the Danone Open at Brisbane, Australia. 
</P>
<P>
Kijimuta repeatedly hit passing shots past Shriver, playing her first 
tournament in nine months after undergoing surgery on her right shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
Shriver, once the third-ranked player in the world and the winner of 21 Grand 
Slam doubles titles during her 13-year professional career, said she wasn't 
downhearted by the loss. "My comeback is a 12- to 18-month project," she said. 
</P>
<P>
At Adelaide, Australia, second-seeded Jim Courier of Dade City, Fla., beat 
Alexander Mronz of Germany 3-6, 6-2, 6-1 in the first round of the Australian 
Hardcourt tennis championship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
